data.name: AssignedByValParameterInspectionMeta
data.value: Parameter is passed by value, but is assigned a new value/reference. Consider making a local copy instead if the caller isn't supposed to know the new value. If the caller should see the new value, the parameter should be passed ByRef instead, and you have a bug.

data.name: ConstantNotUsedInspectionMeta
data.value: Rubberduck could not find any reference to constant. Consider removing the unused declaration.

data.name: EmptyStringLiteralInspection
data.value: Prefer 'vbNullString' to an empty string literal

data.name: EmptyStringLiteralInspectionMeta
data.value: The built-in constant 'vbNullString' is a null string pointer taking up 0 bytes of memory, that unambiguously conveys the intent of an empty string.

data.name: EmptyStringLiteralInspectionQuickFix
data.value: Replace empty string with the 'vbNullString' constant

data.name: ImplicitActiveSheetReferenceInspectionMeta
data.value: Implicit references to the active sheet make the code frail and harder to debug. Consider making these references explicit when they're intended, and prefer working off object references. Ignore if the member call is referring to a type Rubberduck can't resolve.

data.name: ImplicitActiveWorkbookReferenceInspectionMeta
data.value: Implicit references to the active workbook make the code frail and harder to debug. Consider making these references explicit when they're intended, and prefer working off object references. Ignore if the member call is referring to a type Rubberduck can't resolve.

data.name: ImplicitByRefParameterInspectionMeta
data.value: Parameters are passed by reference unless specified otherwise, which can be confusing and bug-prone. Prefer passing parameters by value, and specify ByRef explicitly when passing parameters by reference.

data.name: ImplicitPublicMemberInspectionMeta
data.value: Module members are public by default, which can be counter-intuitive. Consider specifying explicit access modifiers to avoid ambiguity.

data.name: ImplicitVariantReturnTypeInspectionMeta
data.value: Members with a return value implicitly return a 'Variant' unless specified otherwise. Consider returning an explicit 'Variant' when the return type isn't known, or specify it explicitly.

data.name: MoveFieldCloserToUsageInspectionMeta
data.value: A module-level variable used only in one procedure should be declared in that procedure.

data.name: MoveFieldCloserToUsageInspectionName
data.value: Scope of variable is broader than it needs to be

data.name: MoveFieldCloserToUsageInspectionResultFormat
data.value: Move module-level variable '{0}' to a smaller scope.

data.name: MultilineParameterInspectionMeta
data.value: Consider continuing long signatures between parameters. Splitting a parameter declaration across multiple lines arguably hurts readability.

data.name: MultilineParameterInspectionName
data.value: Parameter declaration is split on multiple lines

data.name: MultipleDeclarationsInspectionMeta
data.value: Declaring multiple variables in the same instruction is legal, but should be used sparingly. Consider declaring variables closer to their usage, in a single instruction per declaration.

data.name: MultipleFolderAnnotationsInspectionMeta
data.value: Rubberduck only uses the first '@Folder' annotation in a code module; consider removing extraneous ones.

data.name: MultipleFolderAnnotationsInspectionName
data.value: Module has more than one folder annotation.

data.name: NonReturningFunctionInspectionMeta
data.value: This is likely a bug. The return value of a function or property getter must be assigned before exiting, otherwise the program will not be working with expected results. If a function has no meaningful return value, consider declaring it as a 'Sub' procedure instead.

data.name: ObsoleteCallStatementInspectionMeta
data.value: The 'Call' statement is no longer required to call procedures, and only exists in the language to support legacy code that required it; it can be safely rewritten to an implicit call.

data.name: ObsoleteCommentSyntaxInspectionMeta
data.value: The 'Rem' statement only exists in the language to support legacy code that required it; it can be safely replaced with an apostrophe / single-quote comment.

data.name: ObsoleteGlobalInspectionMeta
data.value: The 'Global' keyword only exists in the language to support legacy code that required it; it can be safely replaced with the 'Public' modifier.

data.name: ObsoleteLetStatementInspectionMeta
data.value: The 'Let' statement only exists in the language to support legacy code that required it; it can be safely removed, since modern VBA does not require that keyword for value assignments.

data.name: ObsoleteTypeHintInspectionMeta
data.value: Type hint characters only exist in the language to support legacy code that required it; they can be safely replaced in declarations with an "As" type clause that specifies the type explicitly, and they can be omitted in other identifier references.

data.name: OptionBaseInspectionMeta
data.value: Arrays are typically zero-based. This option changes the default lower boundary for implicitly-sized arrays, which can introduce off-by-one errors if one isn't cautious.

data.name: OptionExplicitInspectionMeta
data.value: VBA will happily compile a typo: use 'Option Explicit' to prevent successfully compiling an erroneous program.

data.name: ParameterCanBeByValInspectionMeta
data.value: A parameter that is passed by reference and isn't assigned a new value/reference, could be passed by value instead.

data.name: ParameterCanBeByValInspectionName
data.value: Parameter can be passed by value

data.name: ParameterNotUsedInspectionMeta
data.value: A parameter is passed into a member that does not use it. Consider removing that parameter.

data.name: ProcedureNotUsedInspectionMeta
data.value: Rubberduck could not find any caller for a procedure. If the procedure is hooked to a macro-button, used as a user-defined function (UDF) or handles an application event that Rubberduck didn't know of you can safely ignore this inspection result; otherwise, consider removing it.

data.name: UnassignedVariableUsageInspectionMeta
data.value: This is likely a bug. A variable is being referred to, but is never assigned.

data.name: UnassignedVariableUsageInspectionName
data.value: Variable is used but not assigned

data.name: UntypedFunctionUsageInspectionMeta
data.value: A string-returning equivalent function exists and should preferably be used to avoid implicit type conversions. If the parameter can be null, ignore this inspection result; passing a null value to a function expecting a string would raise a type mismatch runtime error.

data.name: ProcedureCanBeWrittenAsFunctionInspectionResultFormat
data.value: Procedure '{0}' can be written as a function.

data.name: ProcedureShouldBeFunctionInspectionQuickFix
data.value: Implement as function and update usages.

data.name: UseMeaningfulNameInspectionMeta
data.value: Identifier names should indicate what they're used for and should be readable; avoid disemvoweling, numeric suffixes, and 1-2 character names.

data.name: VariableNotAssignedInspectionMeta
data.value: Variable does not seem to be assigned. If Rubberduck is correct, the variable could probably be safely removed.

data.name: VariableTypeNotDeclaredInspectionMeta
data.value: A variable whose type isn't explicitly declared, is implicitly 'Variant'. Consider making it an explicit 'Variant' if that's intended, or declare a more specific type.

data.name: WriteOnlyPropertyInspectionMeta
data.value: A property that exposes a mutator but no accessor is a design smell and makes a confusing API. Consider exposing a getter, or converting the mutator to a method.

data.name: ProcedureCanBeWrittenAsFunctionInspectionMeta
data.value: A procedure that only has one parameter passed by reference that is assigned a new value/reference before the procedure exits, is using a ByRef parameter as a return value: consider making it a function instead.

data.name: ProcedureCanBeWrittenAsFunctionInspectionName
data.value: Procedure can be written as a function

data.name: SelfAssignedDeclarationInspectionMeta
data.value: A self-assigned object variable declaration at procedure scope changes how nulling the reference works, which can lead to unexpected behavior.

data.name: FunctionReturnValueNotUsedInspectionName
data.value: Function return value is never used

data.name: FunctionReturnValueNotUsedInspectionResultFormat
data.value: Return value of function '{0}' is never used.

data.name: AssignedByValParameterInspectionResultFormat
data.value: Parameter '{0}' is passed ByVal and assigned a value

data.name: FunctionReturnValueNotUsedInspectionMeta
data.value: A member is written as a function, but used as a procedure. Unless the function is recursive, consider converting the 'Function' into a 'Sub'. If the function is recursive, none of its external callers are using the returned value.

data.name: ImplicitByRefParameterInspectionResultFormat
data.value: Parameter '{0}' is implicitly passed by reference

data.name: ImplicitVariantReturnTypeInspectionResultFormat
data.value: Return type of member '{0}' is implicitly 'Variant'

data.name: MultilineParameterInspectionResultFormat
data.value: Parameter '{0}' is specified on multiple lines

data.name: NonReturningFunctionInspectionResultFormat
data.value: Return value for member '{0}' is never assigned

data.name: ParameterCanBeByValInspectionResultFormat
data.value: Parameter '{0}' can be passed by value

data.name: ProcedureShouldBeFunctionInspectionResultFormat
data.value: Procedure '{0}' can be written as a function

data.name: UnassignedVariableUsageInspectionResultFormat
data.value: Variable '{0}' is used but not assigned

data.name: OptionExplicitInspectionResultFormat
data.value: Option Explicit is not specified in '{0}'

data.name: ReplaceCommentMarkerQuickFix
data.value: Replace 'Rem' usage with a single-quote comment marker

data.name: SplitMultipleDeclarationsQuickFix
data.value: Separate multiple declarations into multiple instructions

data.name: InvalidContextTypeInspectionFix
data.value: Context type '{0}' is not valid for {1}.

data.name: ObjectVariableNotSetInspectionMeta
data.value: As far as Rubberduck can tell, this variable is an object variable, assigned without the 'Set' keyword. This causes run-time error 91 'Object or With block variable not set'.

data.name: ObjectVariableNotSetInspectionResultFormat
data.value: Object variable '{0}' is assigned without the 'Set' keyword

data.name: ObsoleteTypeHintInspectionResultFormat
data.value: {0} of {1} '{2}' uses an obsolete type hint

data.name: UntypedFunctionUsageInspectionResultFormat
data.value: Replace function `{0}` with existing typed function

data.name: MissingAnnotationArgumentInspectionMeta
data.value: An annotation parameter is missing or incorrectly specified. The correct syntax is : '@Annotation([parameter])\nExample: '@Folder("Parent.Child")

data.name: MissingAnnotationArgumentInspectionResultFormat
data.value: Expression '{0}' was expected to contain a parameter, but none was specified.

data.name: ModuleScopeDimKeywordInspectionMeta
data.value: The 'Public' keyword can only be used at module level; its counterpart 'Private' can also only be used at module level. 'Dim' however, can be used to declare both procedure and module scope variables. For consistency, it would be preferable to reserve 'Dim' for locals, and thus to use 'Private' instead of 'Dim' at module level.

data.name: ModuleScopeDimKeywordInspectionName
data.value: Use of 'Dim' keyword at module level

data.name: ModuleScopeDimKeywordInspectionResultFormat
data.value: Module-level variable '{0}' is declared with the 'Dim' keyword.

data.name: UndeclaredVariableInspectionMeta
data.value: Code that uses undeclared variables does not compile when Option Explicit is specified. Undeclared variables are always Variant, a data type that incurs unnecessary overhead and storage.

data.name: ImplicitDefaultMemberAssignmentInspectionMeta
data.value: Such assignments look like they are assigning an object variable to a value type on the surface, but they are actually assigning that object's default member, implicitly. Consider referring to the default member explicitly, for improved readability.

data.name: ImplicitDefaultMemberAssignmentInspectionResultFormat
data.value: Assignment to '{0}' implicitly assigns default member of class '{1}'

data.name: HungarianNotationInspectionMeta
data.value: Hungarian notation makes code less readable, and is redundant when strongly typed variables and meaningful names are used.

data.name: MemberNotOnInterfaceInspectionMeta
data.value: A member access is being used that is not declared on the object's interface. This is most likely an error. If the member access is using the object's extensible interface, consider using a non-extensible equivalent to allow compile time checks that will avoid the possibility of a run-time error 438.

data.name: MemberNotOnInterfaceInspectionName
data.value: Member does not exist on interface

data.name: MemberNotOnInterfaceInspectionResultFormat
data.value: Member '{0}' is not declared on the interface for type '{1}'.

data.name: HostSpecificExpressionInspectionMeta
data.value: Bracketed expressions are evaluated by the host application at runtime, which means VBA can't validate the expression at compile-time. Consider using the host application's object model instead.

data.name: HostSpecificExpressionInspectionName
data.value: Host-specific bracketed expression is only evaluated at runtime

data.name: HostSpecificExpressionInspectionResultFormat
data.value: Expression '{0}' cannot be validated at compile-time.

data.name: ApplicationWorksheetFunctionInspectionMeta
data.value: The Excel Application object does not implement the WorksheetFunction interface directly. All calls made to WorksheetFunction members are handled as late bound and errors in the called member will be returned wrapped in a Variant of VbVarType.vbError. This makes errors un-trappable with error handlers and adds a performance penalty in comparison to early bound calls. Consider calling Application.WorksheetFunction explicitly. Note: If this call generated errors in the past, those errors were ignored. If applying the quick fix, proper error handling should be in place.

data.name: ApplicationWorksheetFunctionInspectionResultFormat
data.value: Use of late bound Application.{0} member.

data.name: AssignedByValParameterMakeLocalCopyQuickFix
data.value: Create and use a local copy of the parameter

data.name: OptionBaseZeroInspectionMeta
data.value: This is the default setting, it does not need to be specified.

data.name: EmptyIfBlockInspectionMeta
data.value: An If block should have executable statements

data.name: EmptyIfBlockInspectionResultFormat
data.value: If block has no executable statements
